"'''Glassheart'''" is a song recorded by British [[singer-songwriter]] [[Leona Lewis]] for her third studio album of [[Glassheart|the same name]] (2012). The song was conceptualised by Lewis and frequent collaborator [[Ryan Tedder]] at his family home in [[Denver, Colorado]]. As she was experiencing a stressful time in her life, Lewis wanted to create an uptempo dance track with Tedder as she felt a ballad would make her more upset. It was co-written by Lewis and Tedder alongside [[Brent Kutzle]], Noel Zancanella, Justin Franks, Fis Shkreli and [[Peter Svensson]]. Production of the song was handled by Tedder and Franks, with the latter credited under his production alias [[DJ Frank E]]. It was co-produced by Zancanella, Kutzle and Shkreli. 

"Glassheart" is an up-tempo [[Dance music|dance]] song that incorporates elements of [[dubstep]], [[Grime music|grime]] and [[house music]]. Lyrically, it is about a woman's fear that her boyfriend will leave her and thus she protects her emotions and her heart from breaking. The song received positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]], many of whom praised the musical direction and its grimy, dubstep breakdown. Upon the release of ''Glassheart'', the song debuted at number 27 on the [[UK Dance Chart]] due to strong [[Music download|digital download]] sales. Lewis has performed the song at London nightclub [[G-A-Y]] and for UK newspaper ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''{{'}}s Biz Sessions.

== Background ==
Lewis began working on her third album ''Glassheart'' in late 2010, shortly after completing her first headlining tour, [[The Labyrinth (tour)|The Labyrinth]].<ref name="3rd album">{{cite interview |last=Lewis |first=Leona |authorlink=Leona Lewis |subjectlink=Leona Lewis |interviewer=[[Rick Edwards]] |title=Under the Skin of Leona Lewis |date=28 February 2010 |publisher=[[4 Music]] |location=[[London]] |format=Television |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lXPKJa1lm0I |accessdate=19 April 2010}}</ref><ref name="Daily Mail 12 Sep 2012">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2202088/Leona-Lewis-plays-intimate-gig-London-nightclub-prepares-return-charts.html |title=Leona Lewis becomes a lady in red for intimate gig in London nightclub as she prepares for return to the charts |work=Daily Mail |publisher=Associated Newspapers |last=Sheridan |first=Emily |date=12 September 2012 |accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> ''Glassheart'' was due to be released in November 2011 after the release of the first single, "[[Collide (Leona Lewis and Avicii song)|Collide]]" (with [[Avicii]]).<ref name="CM Pushbacks">{{cite web |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/leona-lewis-album-pushed-back-again_1287164 |title=Leona Lewis <U+2013> Leona Lewis' Album Pushed Back Again |author=Anon. |publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]] |date=25 January 2012 |accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref> However, in September 2011, Lewis posted a message on her official [[Facebook]] page writing that the album will no longer come out in 2011 as planned, explaining that she was "inspired" to continue making new music and therefore she is personally pushing back the album to early 2012 instead.<ref name="Facebook">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/leonalewis/posts/10150391925577619 |title=Just wanted to... |publisher=[[Facebook]] |last=Lewis |first=Leona |date=26 September 2011 |accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref> That same month, it was announced that the album was expected to be released on 26 March 2012.<ref name="Digital Spy 30 Sep 2011">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a343239/leona-lewis-album-glassheart-release-date-announced.html |title=Leona Lewis album Glassheart release date announced |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] (Hearst Magazines UK) |last=Corner |first=Lewis |date=30 September 2011 |accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref> In December 2011, Lewis released ''[[Hurt: The EP]]'', a collection of [[cover songs]] to bridge the gap between ''[[Echo (Leona Lewis album)|Echo]]'' (2009) and ''Glassheart'' (2012). In January 2012, the album was pushed back again, this time to November 2012, following announcements that Lewis had worked on a track with Scottish DJ [[Calvin Harris]] and [[Fraser T Smith]] would be producing for the album.<ref name="Digital Spy 25 Jan 2012">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a361974/leona-lewis-delays-release-of-third-album-glassheart.html |title=Leona Lewis delays release of third album 'Glassheart' <U+2013> Music News |publisher=Digital Spy (Hearst Magazines UK) |last=Corner |first=Lewis |date=25 January 2012 |accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> Cowell would later publically give his support for ''Glassheart'', declaring to Lewis that although there's been a lengthy wait of two years for new music, "I think this new album is sensational, you<U+2019>ve never sounded better."<ref name="Musicweek 13 Sep 2012">{{cite web |url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/cowell-leona-lewis-saved-x-factor/051774 |title=Simon Cowell: Leona Lewis saved X Factor |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Aek2tAGM |archivedate=13 September 2012 |work=Music Week |publisher=Intent Media |last=Pakinkis |first=Tom |date=13 September 2012 |accessdate=13 September 2012}}</ref>

== Inspiration and development ==
According to Lewis, the song was conceptualised when the singer was experiencing a stressful time in her personal life when she visited her friend and co-writer of the song, [[Ryan Tedder]] in [[Denver, Colorado]].<ref name="Concept Behind Glassheart song">{{cite web|last=Love|first=Ryan|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/interviews/a338818/leona-lewis-interview-i-want-to-give-people-the-best-of-me.html |title=Leona Lewis interview: 'I want to give people the best of me' <U+2013> Music Interview |publisher=Digital Spy (Hearst Magazines UK)|date=6 September 2011 |accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref> The aim of the trip was to visit Tedder and his family, as well as conceive ideas and themes for material to be included on ''Glassheart''.<ref name="Concept Behind Glassheart song"/> Lewis stated that she did not want to sing a ballad which would made her "more sad", therefore they decided to work on an upbeat dance song instead.<ref name="Concept Behind Glassheart song"/> She asked Tedder: "Can you give me a song where I can just dance and jump around?", to which he replied "What about this?" as he played a beat which Lewis found "hypnotic."<ref name="Concept Behind Glassheart song"/> Despite being in a raw form, Lewis was impressed with the song's beat, and said "Yes! We have to do this."<ref name="Concept Behind Glassheart song"/> The collaboration with Tedder marks the third album of Lewis' on which the pair have worked together. They first collaborated on Lewis' debut studio album, ''[[Spirit (Leona Lewis album)|Spirit]]'' (2007), on the songs "[[Bleeding Love]]" and "Take a Bow".<ref name="Spiritalbumnotes">{{cite album-notes |title=Spirit (Liner Notes) |artist=Leona Lewis |year=2007|notestitle= |first=Leona |last=Lewis |authorlink=Leona Lewis |coauthors= |format=Compact Disc |publisher=Syco, J, Sony |p |location=London, England |ref= }}</ref> Tedder also co-wrote songs on Lewis' second studio album, ''[[Echo (Leona Lewis album)|Echo]]'' (2009), "[[Happy (Leona Lewis song)|Happy]]", "You Don't Care" and "Lost then Found", a collaboration with the group Tedder is a member of, [[OneRepublic]].<ref name="Echoalbumnotes">{{cite album-notes |title=Echo (Liner Notes) |artist=Leona Lewis |year=2009|notestitle= |first=Leona |last=Lewis |authorlink=Leona Lewis |coauthors= |format=Compact Disc |publisher=Syco, J, Sony |p |location=London, England |ref= }}</ref> In addition to the title track on ''Glassheart'', Lewis and Tedder collaborated on the song "Favourite Scar".<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes">{{cite album-notes |title=Glassheart (Liner Notes) |artist=Leona Lewis |year=2012|notestitle= |first=Leona |last=Lewis |authorlink=Leona Lewis |coauthors= |format=Compact Disc |publisher=Syco |p |location=London, England |ref= }}</ref>

== Recording ==
[[File:Ryan Tedder OneRepublic Austria 3.jpg|thumb|140px|alt=A picture of a man wearing a hat|Lewis and [[Ryan Tedder]] ''(pictured)'' conceptualised the idea for "Glassheart" while she visited him at his home in Denver, Colorado<ref name="Concept Behind Glassheart song"/>]]
"Glassheart" was co-written by Lewis with Tedder, [[Brent Kutzle]], Noel Zancanella, Justin Franks, Fis Shkreli and [[Peter Svensson]].<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes"/> It was produced by Tedder and Franks, who is credited under his production name [[DJ Frank E]]; the song was co-produced by Zancanella, Kutzle and Shkreli.<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes"/> The song was [[Music engineer|engineered]] by Smith Carlson, Mike Freesh and Sam Wheat; they were in assisted in the process by Tom Hough, while Daniela Rivera provided additional engineering.<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes"/> "Glassheart" was [[Mixing (music production)|mixed]] by [[Phil Tan]] at the Ninja Beat Club in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]; it was [[Mastering engineer|mastered]] by Colin Leonard at SING Mastering, also in Atlanta, using SING Technology.<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes"/> [[Instrumentation]] of the song was provided for by multiple musicians: Shkreli was appointed head of [[sound design]], and was also a [[Drum machine|drum programmer]] along with Freesh and Trent Mazour.<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes"/> The guitarist enlisted for the song was Mazour, while Freesh served as the [[bassist]].<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes"/> The pair also provided the [[Synthesizer|synths]].<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes"/> All other forms of instrumentation were performed by Tedder.<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes"/> "Glassheart" was recorded at several recording locations around the world, including Patriot Studios, Denver, Colarado; [[Westlake Recording Studios]], [[Los Angeles, California]]; [[Side 3 Studios]], [[Hollywood, California]] and [[Metropolis Studios]], [[London, England]].<ref name="Glassheartalbumnotes"/>

== Composition and lyrics ==
"Glassheart" is a [[dubstep]]<ref name="JennaMTVBuzzworthy"/>, [[Dance music|dance]],<ref name="IdolatorFirstListenGlassheartSong">{{cite web|last=Lansky|first=Sam|url=http://idolator.com/6923372/leona-lewis-glassheart-song-listen |title=Leona Lewis Glassheart Listen|work=''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|publisher=[[Buzz Media]]|date=20 September 2012|accessdate=25 october 2012}}</ref> [[House music|house]] and [[Grime (music)|grime]]<ref name="CarolineGuardianReview"/> song that runs for 3:56 (three minutes, 56 seconds).<ref name="iTunesGlassheartStandard"/> According to Jenna Hally Rubenstein for [[MTV|MTV Buzzworthy]], the song consists of a "grimy, hazy beat", which she compared to "[[Too Close (Alex Clare song)|Too Close]]" (''[[The Lateness of the Hour (album)|The Lateness of the Hour]]'', 2011), a song performed by [[Alex Clare]].<ref name="JennaMTVBuzzworthy"/> Lyrically, the song is about Lewis' fear that her lover will break her heart.<ref name="DigitalSpyAlbumReview">{{cite web|last=Corner|first=Lewis|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/albumreviews/a430007/leona-lewis-glassheart-album-review.html|title=Leona Lewis: 'Glassheart' <U+2013> Album Review|work=''Digital Spy''|publisher=Hearst Magazines UK|date=11 October 2012|accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref> According to Lewis, the song is about protecting yourself, your heart, as well as your emotions.<ref name="RadioInterview">Leona Lewis Interview. Clyde 1 Radio. (Global Radio Group). [Radio Interviewer]. Aired 17 September 2012.</ref> She continued to describe the song as "poignant".<ref name="RadioInterview"/> The singer went on to reveal that she decided to name the album after the song.<ref name="RadioInterview"/> Lewis' "crisp" vocals can be heard above the [[instrumentation]] as she "croons about the fragility of her heart" as she performs the [[Refrain|chorus]] lines "So baby if you love me/ Let me know/ 'Cause everything hurts just like before/ You're about to tear this heart apart/ I love you like a glass heart."<ref name="JennaMTVBuzzworthy"/> The chorus is built on a "transcendent house beat" as Lewis delicately sings the lines "Promise that we'll never fall apart/ And I'll love you with my Glassheart".<ref name="IdolatorFirstListenGlassheartSong"/> The chorus is then followed by a "euphoric instrumentation [that] collapses into a grimy dubstep break."<ref name="IdolatorFirstListenGlassheartSong"/> Rubenstein likened the the lyrics to those performed by [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]] on her song "[[Heart of Glass (song)|Heart of Glass]]" (''[[Parallel Lines]]'', 1978).<ref name="JennaMTVBuzzworthy"/>

== Critical reception==
Jenna Hally Rubenstein for MTV Buzzworthy was complimentary of the song, writing that Lewis had "[upped] the musical ante big time".<ref name="JennaMTVBuzzworthy">{{cite web|last=Rubenstein|first=Jenna Hally|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2012/09/21/leona-lewis-glassheart-new-song/|title=New Song: Leona Lewis, 'Glassheart'|work=''[[MTV|MTV Buzzworthy]]''|publisher=[[Viacom]]|date=21 September 2012|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> Rubenstein continued to highly praise the inclusion of the dubstep transition due to the fact that she thought she would never "use the words 'dubstep' and 'Leona Lewis' in the same sentence."<ref name="JennaMTVBuzzworthy"/> Caroline Sullivan for ''[[The Guardian]]'' described the song as "mood elevating with an abrasive grime beat."<ref name="CarolineGuardianReview">{{cite news|last=Sullivan|first=Caroline|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2012/oct/11/leona-lewis-glassheart-review?newsfeed=true |title=Leona Lewis: Glassheart <U+2013> review|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media]]|date=11 October 2012 |accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> Matthew Horton for [[Virgin Media]] described the song as "unexpectedly ravey".<ref name="VirginMediaReview">{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Matthew|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/music/reviews/leona-lewis-glassheart.php|title=Leona Lewis <U+2013> Glassheart <U+2013> Review|publisher=[[Virgin Media]]|date=12 October 2012|accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref> Chris Smith for [[Yahoo! Music|Yahoo!]] described the song as a curveball and wrote that he felt it is Lewis' "first truly club friendly track".<ref name="YahooReview">{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Chirs|url=http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/album-review-leona-lewis-glassheart-175100247.html|title=Album Review: Leona Lewis- Glassheart|work=[[Yahoo! Music]]|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|date=21 October 2012|accessdate=26 October 2012}}</ref> Sam Lanksy for [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] thought that although song is radio-friendly, it is not "derivative".<ref name="IdolatorFirstListenGlassheartSong"/>

== Live performances ==
Lewis debuted the song at London nightclub [[G-A-Y]] on 5 September 2011; she performed the song as part of a mini [[set-list]] along with "Collide" and "Bleeding Love".<ref name="G.A.Y">{{cite web|last=Love|first=Ryan|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a338806/leona-lewis-debuts-hypnotic-third-album-glassheart-title-track-video.html|title=Exclusive: Leona Lewis debuts 'hypnotic' third album 'Glassheart' title track: Video|work=''Digital Spy''|publisher=Hearst Magazines UK|date=5 September 2011|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> The performance featured Lewis performing a "raunchy" dance routine with partially nude male dancers.<ref name="TheSunGAY">{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/x_factor/3794262/Leona-Lewis-raunchy-dance-moves.html|title=Leona Lewis's raunchy dance moves|work=The Sun|publisher=News International|date=5 September 2011|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Lewis wore a black knee length dress, with a red heart emblem across her chest.<ref name="TheSunGAY"/> Nadia Sam-Dalir for ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' wrote that the singer had "dumped her demure image" in favour of "her raunchiest-ever dance routine surrounded by muscly bare-chested hunks."<ref name="TheSunGAY"/> Prior to the release of ''Glassheart'' in October 2012, Lewis performed the acoustic version of the song as part of another mini set-list for British newspaper ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''{{'}}s Biz Sessions, along with the lead single from the album, "[[Trouble (Leona Lewis song)|Trouble]]", and a cover of Alex Clare's "Too Close".<ref name="TheSunBIZ">{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/bizarre/bizsessions/4570108/Leona-Lewis-performs-Biz-Session.html|title=Leona Lewis performs Biz Session|work=The Sun|publisher=News International|date=6 October 2012|accessdate=27 October 2012}}</ref>

